SIMPLE: scatter
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scatter
<hw>Scat"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Scattered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Scattering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>scateren</ets>. See <er>Shatter</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
strew about; to sprinkle around; to throw down loosely; to deposit or
place here and there, esp. in an open or sparse order.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And some are <qex>scattered</qex> all the floor about.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Why should my muse enlarge on Libyan swains,⟦br⟧
Their <qex>scattered</qex> cottages, and ample plains?</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Teach the glad hours to <qex>scatter</qex>, as they fly,⟦br⟧
Soft quiet, gentle love, and endless joy.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cause to separate in different directions; to
reduce from a close or compact to a loose or broken order; to dissipate;
to disperse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Scatter</qex> and disperse the giddy Goths.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hence, to frustrate, disappoint, and overthrow;
<as>as, to <ex>scatter</ex> hopes, plans, or the like</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To disperse; dissipate; spread; strew.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scatter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scatter
<hw>Scat"ter</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be dispersed or dissipated;
to disperse or separate; <as>as, clouds <ex>scatter</ex> after a
storm</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scatter-brain</ent>⟦br⟧
